{"type":"assistant.message","data":{"messageId":"a7fae819-11a0-41eb-a4ac-8a7b017ad394","content":"Here's how to collect a CPU trace from a .NET 8 app in a Windows container on Kubernetes:\n\n### 1. Exec into the container\n```bash\nkubectl exec -it <pod-name> -- powershell\n```\n\n### 2. Install `dotnet-trace`\n```powershell\ndotnet tool install -g dotnet-trace\n```\n\n### 3. Find the process ID\n```powershell\ndotnet-trace ps\n```\n\n### 4. Collect the trace\n```powershell\ndotnet-trace collect -p <PID> --profile cpu-sampling --duration 00:00:30\n```\n\nThis writes a `.nettrace` file you can analyze in **Visual Studio** or **PerfView**.\n\n### To copy it out\n```bash\nkubectl cp <pod-name>:/path/to/trace.nettrace ./trace.nettrace\n```\n\n### Alternative: `dotnet-counters` for a quick look first\n```powershell\ndotnet tool install -g dotnet-counters\ndotnet-counters monitor -p <PID> --counters System.Runtime\n```\nThis gives live CPU %, GC, threadpool stats — useful before committing to a full trace.\n\n> **Tip:** If `dotnet tool` isn't on the PATH inside the container, the tools install to `~/.dotnet/tools` — use the full path.","toolRequests":[],"interactionId":"52500005-1a7a-44e2-ba53-0f3b505b12b5","reasoningOpaque":"","reasoningText":"The user is asking for guidance on collecting a performance trace from a .NET 8 application running in a Windows container on Kubernetes, where they're experiencing high CPU. This is a diagnostic/troubleshooting question, not a code change request. I'll provide concise guidance.","outputTokens":399,"requestId":"7664:2C695B:E021AD:10423BC:69FE8C9A"},"id":"135eb271-0cad-4e14-bead-bd5faf3955c1","timestamp":"2026-05-09T01:23:46.946Z","parentId":"ab1817a6-aece-41c4-b446-d5b1e4dc3362"}
